            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36.11"/>
                
                <note>
                    Ans. 2-9-72
                    (dictated)
                </note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">11</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">MILDRED R. BENNETT</hi> 
                        <lb/>
                    329 North Cedar
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps">RED CLOUD, NEBRASKA</hi> 68970 
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Jan. 26, 1972</dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>5835 Vine Street</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebr. 68505</addrLine>
                    </address>
                        
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you for your good letter. I appreciate your sending me a copy of President Nixon's birthday greetings to you. That was a very nice letter.</p>
                
                <p>Have you ever heard of <hi rend="caps">T.</hi> Lobsang Rampa? He is a Ti<del>e</del><add>b</add>etan lama who has written a number of books dealing with mysticism and the philosophy of Tibet. He tells many things that would be of great interest to you and that fit in with your beliefs.</p>
                
                <p>For instance he describes things he has seen in astral traveling that sound like the ones you describe in the spirit world in <hi rend="caps">CYCLE OF THE WEST</hi>. He, of course, believes in reincarnation. It is easy to see after reading him how you could say that the Indians were the winners at the battle of Wounded Knee. They realized values not of this world.</p>
                
                <p>I am glad you had a good birthday. Mrs. Sherwood is now 102 and has been sort of in a coma for a long time, but lately she has been alert and I have been able to talk to her and bring her up to date on things going on at the Cather Memorial.</p>
                
                <p>I hope you did not get the flu. Someone said you had been in the hospital with pneumonia. I hope that is all over with now. We have had a lot of flu in this part of the country but so far we have escaped it in this household.</p> <note>tell g stay in hospital <hi rend="underline">Dec 4 to 15</hi> <unclear/> Lincoln <unclear>Dec 18</unclear></note> 
                
                <note>Comment &#8212;</note> <p>I have sent for a review copy of your autobiography. The <hi rend="underline">Western Literature Magazine</hi> wants me to review it for them as soon as it comes out. I am eager to read it myself.</p> 
                
                <p>What a blessing you have been to the world and how great was the day when I first met you and had a chance to talk with you.</p> 
                
                <p>With this cold weather I suppose you are kept indoors most of the time, but spring is not far off.</p>
                
                <note>Poor - Alicia</note> <p>I hope I get to visit with you again before too long. Did I tell you that Alicia cried because she didn't get to see you when you were here for the Western Literature Associa<del/><add>t</add>ion?</p> 
                
                <p>Love from the whole household.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Mildred</signed> 
                    <signed>Mildred</signed> 
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
